<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="generic diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Generic diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Body shape of adult female variable: oblong, fusiform, obovate, or oval. Antennae with 2 or more setae. Prominent median lobes with short inner edges, long outer margins, and conspicuous scleroses and paraphyses. A pair of small gland spines between lobes. Second lobes greatly reduced or absent and 4-6 marginal macroducts present on each side of pygidium. Anal opening in anterior portion of pygidium or near apex. Vulva either without perivulvar pores or surrounded by three or five groups of them (
<bibRefCitation author="Takagi, S" journalOrPublisher="Insecta Matsumurana" pageId="8" pageNumber="25" pagination="93 - 119" title="Some Diaspididae of Japan (Homoptera: Coccoidea)." volume="28" year="1966">Takagi and Kawai 1966</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Takagi, S" journalOrPublisher="Insecta Matsumurana" pageId="8" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 142" title="Diaspididae of Taiwan based on material collected in connection with the Japan-U. S. Co-operative Science Programme, 1965 (Homoptera: Coccoidea) Part II." volume="33" year="1970">Takagi 1970</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Williams, DJ" journalOrPublisher="CAB International, Wallingford" pageId="8" pageNumber="25" title="The Scale Insects of the Tropical South Pacific Region. Pt. 1: The Armoured Scales (Diaspididae)." year="1988">Williams and Watson 1988</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
